This is the generic term; it is commonly used with other morphemes for other body parts, e.g. 'spine' 04.191; 'skull' 04.202; 'jaw' 04.207. See also 04.142, for a similar use of 'hair'.
-wa is the generic word. Other forms of 'hair' are expressed by naming the part of the body involved. The body part 'bone' also forms words in this way.
'Head hair' is -patik a-wa, lit. 'head (poss.)-hair'. See 04.142. Probably has basic meaning of 'covering'. Also means 'feather' 04.393; 'wool' 06.220; 'fur' 06.280; 'leaf' 08.560.

Means 'the insides spread out/are squeezed/work/suffer/are strong/gape/wait'. wathwuk is lit. 'insides', and is used to translate 'mind', see 17.110.

Lit. 'insides'. As seen in Section 16, this word is used in many expressions, especially concerning emotions and feelings; see 'joyful'16.230; also 'idea' 17.190. -wathwuk is also used in a physical sense, 'the inside of something', e.g. mekyi aksak awathwuk 'nothing inside it/empty'.
Can be translated as -ki-lkyitam-kyi -(poss)-wathwuk, lit. 'the insides search'; cf. 17.110.
Powys (ca. 1935: 8) also gives ma, mai, the answer to a question. Also ikhawe meaning 'not, not that'; meko, 'there is no/none' or 'without'.
This word is used to speak of a person's soul (16.110), usually after death.
